<section class="pains" aria-label="Why Eleven exists">
  <h2>Ever wondered&hellip;</h2>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why is chatting to your friends run by big tech?</h3>
    <p>
      A group chat with your actual friends doesn't need a social network
      wrapped around it. It doesn't need an algorithm deciding what you see,
      and it definitely doesn't need a business model that runs on knowing
      who you talk to.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why do you need a mobile number to talk to people you already know?</h3>
    <p>
      Your phone number is an identity you hand over before you've even said
      hello. Eleven skips accounts entirely — you join with a secret link
      from someone already inside.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why choose between owning your chat and actually enjoying it?</h3>
    <p>
      You don't need to self-host Eleven, but if you do, it's designed to be
      as simple as possible. Push notifications just work via a shared relay,
      and keys can be backed up on our shared secure home server, both
      optional.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="attrs" aria-label="What Eleven is">
  <h2>Eleven is&hellip;</h2>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Familiar and easy</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        You shouldn't have to learn how Eleven works. Click a link and
        you're chatting. It's one click to save your chats so you don't
        lose them: no signup required.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Open</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Eleven is not run by a corporation or a big organisation. Get started
        easily if you're invited to an existing space through the Eleven apps.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Secure</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        In a world where too many apps end up &ldquo;not secure&rdquo;, Eleven
        is designed to be &ldquo;secure enough&rdquo;. The basic principle is:
        if the server got hacked, nothing on the server should expose
        anything. And that's how it is. Private chats are completely secret to
        the two participants, group chats are secret to the group. That's it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Web-based</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Eleven stores messages on a server on the web. This allows freedom to
        use Eleven on different devices. Browser window? Check. PWA with push
        notifications? Check. Eleven doesn't shy away from being a web
        application.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Native</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Even though Eleven is entirely web-based, starting with iOS and Mac,
        Eleven's apps are native where it matters: in the feels. They're fast,
        quick to download, and don't hog your system resources.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>Tracking-free</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        There are no trackers associated with Eleven at all. Anything that
        personally identifies you remains secret. That's it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="attr">
    <h3>AI-enabled</h3>
    <div class="attr-body">
      <p>
        Frustratingly, all of the above attributes mean that no corporation
        has so far been compelled to produce an app like Eleven, with
        world-class user experience, and absolute respect for the human using
        the product. AI enables the production of the kind of product that we
        wish big tech had, at a fraction of the cost.
      </p>
      <p>
        Eleven is built with the latest AI models, and audited by them too,
        including a security review by Claude&nbsp;Fable. We're in beta with
        the source open, so nobody has to take our word for any of that. Check
        the code yourself.
      </p>
      <p>
        Additionally, AI agents can optionally be added to Eleven to do some
        interesting (or stranger) things.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="creed" aria-label="What Eleven proves">
  <p>
    <span class="creed-lead">Eleven is proof</span> that we can have great
    user experience, good-enough security, openness and respect for the user
    as a person and not an eyeball to be monetised.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="feature-group" aria-label="Feature highlights">
  <h2>More than you'd expect</h2>
  <p class="section-sub">
    All the chat things, done properly — and then a few things no other
    messenger has.
  </p>
  <ul class="cards">
    <li>
      <h3>Everything where you are</h3>
      <p>
        Start a conversation on your Mac, answer on your phone, catch up in
        any browser. Read messages stay read, everywhere.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Apps built by asking</h3>
      <p>
        Ask for &ldquo;a holiday packing list&rdquo; or &ldquo;a habit
        tracker&rdquo; and a little app appears right in your chat, made for
        your group alone.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Helpers on a schedule</h3>
      <p>
        &ldquo;Send me a news summary every morning.&rdquo; Set up little
        helpers that do things for your group, on your terms.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Your space, your rules</h3>
      <p>
        You (or someone you trust) runs the space. Decide who's in, what's
        open, and even charge for membership — the money goes to you, not us.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p style="margin-top: 1.25rem">
    <a href="/features/">See everything Eleven does &rarr;</a>
  </p>
</section>

<section class="feature-group" id="pricing" aria-label="Pricing">
  <h2>What it costs</h2>
  <p class="section-sub">
    Joining a space someone invited you to is always free. Creating spaces is
    free too — paid plans add storage and keep Eleven running with no ads and
    no investors.
  </p>
  <div class="plans">
    <div class="plan">
      <h3>Free</h3>
      <span class="price">&euro;0</span>
      <p>
        Every feature. Create up to three spaces, with 1&nbsp;GB of photos
        and files each.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="plan">
      <h3>Family</h3>
      <span class="price">&euro;5<small>/year</small></span>
      <p>
        5&nbsp;GB of storage, and your space is never tidied away as unused.
        One coffee, once a year.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="plan">
      <h3>Community &amp; Friends</h3>
      <span class="price">&euro;4<small>/month</small></span>
      <p>
        10&nbsp;GB, for clubs, teams, and bigger circles.
      </p>
      <span class="alt">or &euro;40/year</span>
    </div>
    <div class="plan">
      <h3>Business</h3>
      <span class="price">&euro;99<small>/month</small></span>
      <p>
        25&nbsp;GB, for a small business that wants its chat out of big
        tech's hands.
      </p>
      <span class="alt">or &euro;999/year</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p class="fine" style="margin-top: 1.25rem">
    Every plan is every feature — privacy is never the paid tier. Storage
    allowances are deliberately roomy for how spaces actually get used, and
    they'll grow. Upgrade any time from
    <a href="https://home.elevenmessenger.com">your home page</a>; payment
    happens on Stripe's secure page, so we never see your card, name, or
    email.
  </p>
</section>

